metadata.name: Focused MINd #4
metadata.description:
Although it looks like this piece is a metaphor for a focused mind, actually the title was chosen after the piece was finished :-) .

Basically a focused mind have a more or less clear direction but, no matter how deep in the flow one is, there are occasional thought that stray away and choose their own path.


The piece is built entirely on thi.ng/umbrella libraries and template:

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

Initial resolution: 1280 x 720

Keyboard shortcuts

- 2 : download png @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : download png @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution
- s : download SVG version @ current resolution

metadata.name: Organic Oeuvre #17
metadata.description:
First project on FXHash.

Entirely coded in p5js.

Stochastic strokes while ensuring randomness is consistent; uses 500+ color palettes.

The pieces created by this project are dynamic and change based on the size of the viewing window ("organic"), making each viewing experience unique. 

In case you find a bug, please consider it an easter egg! Write to me on twitter if you think it's a bug and I'll send another couple your way from my reserved :)

Press s to save the image in fullscreen.

metadata.name: V'Ger #1
metadata.description:
V'Ger

This piece is an amalgamation of influences and algorithms. Epoff (c.1969) an oil painting by Victor Vasarely as well as M.C.Escher tessellations. Surface displacement and coloring algorithms by Christopher Scussel. 

After I developed the basic tile to tesselate the surface I randomized everything I could. It was only when I started seeing latent images in my head that remined me of an old movie: Star Trek: The Motion Picture (1979) that I knew I was finished playing around.

This image is dedicated to my mermaid and partner. She is my muse and source of inspiration. Published on Valentine's Day, 2023 in her honor.

Enjoy.

Please visit http://www.drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.name: Bayerlinge #100
metadata.description:
"Bayerlinge" is motivated by the artworks of Herbert Bayer (1900-1985). The Upper Austrian born artist spent his life in Germany and the United Stated and also worked as graphic designer, painter, and many more.

I was inspired by his piece "Foursome" from 1971 and aimed to deliver the same feeling in a generative setting. The token expands upon Bayer's arrangement, adding different shapes and for more than the overlapping 2x2 setup.

The key press "s" or "S" lets you save a high resolution image.
